Author: Siemens, George; d Baker, Ryan SJ
Title: Learning analytics and educational data mining: towards communication and collaboration
Publication Title: Proceedings of the 2nd international conference on learning analytics and knowledge
Short Title: Learning analytics and educational data mining
Notes:
Siemens & Baker 2012 Notes

  • Article briefly outlines emergence of EDM and LAK and explains differences and similarities between the fields.
  • Argues for greater collaboration between EDM and LAK given their similarities, they are in many ways compatible and have complimentary goals; their slightly different approaches can also spur advancement in each field. Also...allows field as a whole to grow, and more researchers to be available to work on research.
  • Formal definitions from both on pages 2 and 3.
  • Comparison between fields summarised by:

Title: Video: Why Is Measuring Learning So Difficult?
Abstract Note: From analytics to teaching and learning, several higher ed professionals weigh in on the challenge of attempting to measure comprehension.
Notes:
Video: Why is measuring learning so difficult? Notes

  • Amy Collier:
    • Learning is multi-dimensional and measuring it means simplifying something so complex in order to capture data.
    • Learning is a "black box", making it difficult to capture and analyze data.
  • Daniel Hickey:
    • Learning is too broad, measuring it in a psychometric way is nearly impossible. Knowledge is so bound to the context where it is used that its hard to measure in a psychometrically sound way.
    • Hard to measure competencies coming into an environment- i.e. without a baseline you can't really measure improvement.
    • Difference in measuring competence versus learning. Learning can be thought of as multiple measures of competence strung together that are associated with a a particular learning experience.
  • Justin Reich:
    • Fields in the humanities, tools for measuring learning are much weaker.
    • Measuring is a construct. When we talk about measuring we are talking about psychological constructs- such as achievement.
  • Ellen Wagner:
    • Learning is a highly personal experience, the construct of learning is very difficult to define and measure. You can measure behaviors and outputs but not cognitive development or activity.
  • Gardner Campbell:
    • There are no reliable, proxy indicators that we can trust. Can't measure cognition (i.e. can't measure understanding) but can measure indicators of understanding (i.e. when learning crosses multiple domains).
    • Who and why are you measuring learning for? Talks about students knowing about their learning to reflect on it. Believes analytics should be for the learner and not just a diagnosis but a discussion.

Author: University of Technology Sydney, Australia; Knight, Simon; Buckingham Shum, Simon; University of Technology Sydney, Australia
Title: Theory and Learning Analytics
Notes:
Knight & Shum, 2017 Notes

  • Knight and Shum argue the "use of a learning analytics tool is always aligned with assesment regimes" and that this in turn reflect assumptions around what knowledge is an how to measure it, as well as pedagogical approaches.
  • Those in LA need to be conscious of this and their decisions when designing or implementing the tool as this can draw attention to one particular measure of knowledge/ learning (and linked pedagogy) and away from others.
    •  We need to think about how LA tools "enhance/ constrain theorizing by virtue of what they draw attention to, and what they ignore or downplay" p.17
  • LA designers have a responsibility to have their "eyes wide open to the risks of distorting our definition of "learning" in our desire to track it computationally." p18 YES YES YES!
    • "We measure what we value" p.19--> not sure I agree...don't we instead come to value what we can measure???
    • LA, as assessment tools, have a sort of emancipatory potential to it- can challenge existing education assumptions and structures. p.19
  • Benefits of this data revolution is that LA brings "people in the analytic loop" so the "system becomes reflexive" p.18.
    •  This allows teachers and learners to engage in understanding and following their own learning journey (IF it is clear they are viewing only one piece of a wider learning puzzle).
  • Authors' belief is that because of the above, theory is MORE important when analyzing big data than ever before- unlike some arguments in the field.
    • They prefer the more nuanced terms of "Data Geology" and "Data Archeology" to data mining.
  • Authors' "heuristic guide" for LA includes three key questions:
    1.    What is being measured? i.e. what does knowledge look like in this particular approach? p.19
      •   Links theoretical understanding of knowledge with practical method for measuring it.
      • "This is a question of epistemology; it concerns the nature of the constructs, why they "count" as knowledge," p.19
    2. How are we measuring? i.e. assessment methodology linked to the particular epistemological assumptions made in question 2. p.20
    3. Why is this particular knowledge important?
      •  Measuring what we value as a society, or what we need for an economy (FUNCTIONALIST!! HCT!)
      • This is a reflection, in my opinion, of sociological beliefs about schooling.
    4. Who is the assessment for?
      •  Who are the beneficiaries/ end users?
      • What level are the insights going to be at (national, systems, school, individual)?
      • This also affects the output/ usage.
      • Note....ethical concerns about targeting specific groups, about using data, about access if tech is required to access that analytic tool. p.20
    5. Where does the assessment happen?
      •  How might this affect the outcome/ "biases particular kinds of response". Certain metrics might favor certain types of students or teaching! p.21
      • Concerns about reliability and viability.
      • Can't isolate the tool from the context.
    6. When does it all take place (assessment & feedback)?
      • Summative? Formative? Post-learning or real-time results? Monitoring or evaluation?
Editor: Columbia University, USA; Lang, Charles; Siemens, George; University of Texas at Arlington, USA; Wise, Alyssa; New York University, USA; Gasevic, Dragan; University of Edinburgh, UK

Author: Greller, Wolfgang; Drachsler, Hendrik
Title: Translating learning into numbers: A generic framework for learning analytics
Notes:
Geller & Drachsler, 2012, Notes

  • Authors have developed a design framework meant to help guide LA activities.
  • One of main aguments is that more guidance on ethics, data ownership and data management is needed, particularly at the university level. This is because without these, there is a danger that learning data "provides a tool for HEIs, companies, or government to increase manipulative control" p.13
  • They have conceptualized six critical dimensions of LA in an effort to encourage a "bottom-up approach" to LA where learners are at the heart of all LA efforts. p.13
    • Soft: challenges around how humans or the context they are in work.
    • Hard: technical challenges linked to data and algorithms etc
  • Six dimensions are:
    • External limitations.
      • Conventions.
      • Norms. 
    • Internal limitations.
      • Competences.
      • Acceptance.
    • Instruments.
      • Technology.
      • Algorithm.
      • Theories.
      • Other.
    •  Data.
      • Protected.
      • Open.
    • Objectives.
      • Prediction.
      • Reflection.
    • Stakeholders.
      • Institution.
      • Teachers.
      • Learners.
      • Other.
  • Creates a hierarchical model of information flow from students to teachers to the institutions and government/ policy by way of self-reflection and research.
    • Can also be a horizontal flow of information via peer evaluation. p.5
    • Note- it's interesting how students are at the bottom- the first to generate data but the last to  (be able to) do anything with it????
  • Six dimensions above are pretty self-explanatory, pp.5-13. Interesting points noted below.
  • On Data:
    • Authors talk about issues around data ownership and access to data- who owns student data?
    • Also dicuss difficulties of dealing with data without consensus on data format, version control, data anonymization and overall standardization of data documentation. p.8
    • More importantly, authors argue the challenge remains to have USEFUL data: "...idealised datasets probably remain the biggest challenge for analytics"
  • On External Constraints:
    •  Range from ethical and social constraints (conventions) to organizational, legal and process constraints (norms). p.9
    • Although legal frameworks have been established in many contexts which dictate terms of data privacy, data ownership continues to lack clarity.
    • In education settings, datasets from different departments/ teams needs to be better integrated.
  • On pedagogy and the LA framework:
    •  Seem to be arguing some LA lends itself better to some learning theories than others (e.g. behaviorist models). Need to look more into this.
    • But in Geller & Drachsler's model the pedagogy used and measured is implicit in the datasets- i.e. the outputs are sort of reflections on the pedagogy itself, - "pedagogy behaviour". Though, it is noted that pedagogy also informs beliefs, values and epistemological assumptions.
    • However, "pedagogy can be explicitly addressed in the goals and objectives that the LA designer sets" p.12

Author: University of South Africa, South Africa; Prinsloo, Paul; Slade, Sharon; The Open University, United Kingdom
Title: Ethics and Learning Analytics: Charting the (Un)Charted
Notes:
Prinsloo & Slade, 2017 Notes

  • The chapter charts the debate and developments in ethics within learning analytics. The authors provide an overview of literature and frameworks proposed since the emergence of the field.
    •     Argue that we are seeing "ethics and privacy as crucial enablers" in LA p.49.
  • Overall, it must be noted that the maturing of the field has brought with it greater focus on ethics and ethical practice, and while there is some agreement on general approaches towards ethical behavior and use of data, a codified set of 'rules' is lacking, even within institutions.
    •   However, it seems the authors think we are working towards this and all the discussion have contributed to a growing body of understanding and refined thinking.
    • "The practical implementation of that understanding remains largely incomplete, but still wholly pertinent." p.55
  • Current context of LA means more need than ever for ethical codes of practice etc: more concerns about AI and big data, and also more vested interests in securing and using data- profitable business. p.52
    •     "...the increasing value of data as a shareable commodity with an increasing exchange value has overtaken our legal and traditional ethical frameworks" p.52
  • Various frameworks, policies and models outlined in article- from academic arguments to HEI policies, and even national (UK) papers. Generally, some of key issues covered include:
    • Location & analysis of data.
    • Securing informed consent from students (including opt-out option).
    • Engaging and involving stakeholders- from students to teachers.
    • Ensuring data privacy and non-personalized data.
    • Transparent and ethical organization and categorization of data.
    • Only analyzing data that is relevant.
    • Preventing data analysis to
    • Human oversight of algorithms, more transparency across algorithms, or implementing algorithm-audits.
    • Not allowing data to define students, their ability and potential (i.e. it is a snapshot).
    • Student data only used in line with original aims of collecting data.
    • Allowing appeals for decisions made based on data.
  • The usefulness of LA and data is not contested, though limitations are identified (e.g. "over-analysis", or "lack of generalizability" p.52
  • Basically, see institutions as going to establish policies, frameworks or rules around data collection and use in future. Also codes of practice within LA field. Suggest we need a more critical approach to thinking about ethics in LA.
